a)

We have the following random effect model

yij=β0+β1x+γ0i+γ1ix+ϵij(1)(1)yij=β0+β1x+γ0i+γ1ix+ϵij
where γi=[γ0iγ1i]Tγi=[γ0iγ1i]T are binormally distributed with zero mean and variance matrix

[τ20τ01τ01τ21][τ02τ01τ01τ12]
and εijεij are iid N(0,σ2)N(0,σ2) for i=1,…,mi=1,…,m and j=1,…,ni.j=1,…,ni. The remaining terms of (1) can be written as vectors

β=[β0β1]T,β=[β0β1]T, xij=[1xij]Txij=[1xij]T and uij=[1xij]T.uij=[1xij]T.

For a specific cluster ii equation (1) takes the following form

yi=Xiβ+Uiγi+εi,i=1,⋯,m,(2)(2)yi=Xiβ+Uiγi+εi,i=1,⋯,m,
where

yi=[yi1⋯yini]T,yi=[yi1⋯yini]T, Xi=[xTi1⋯xTini]T,Xi=[xi1T⋯xiniT]T, Ui=[uTi1⋯uTini]TUi=[ui1T⋯uiniT]T and εi=[εi1⋯εini]T.εi=[εi1⋯εini]T.

Finally we can write the generic LMM equation

y=Xβ+Uγ+ε,(3)(3)y=Xβ+Uγ+ε,
where

y=[y1⋯yi⋯ym]T,y=[y1⋯yi⋯ym]T, ε=[ε1⋯εi⋯εm]T,ε=[ε1⋯εi⋯εm]T, γ=[γ1⋯γi⋯γm]Tγ=[γ1⋯γi⋯γm]T and U=blogdiag(U1,…Ui,…Um).U=blogdiag⁡(U1,…Ui,…Um).

b)

mylmm = function(y, x, group, REML = FALSE, start=c(1,1,0,1)) {
  library(Matrix)
  n = length(y)
  m = nlevels(group)
  #X = cbind(1,x)
  X = model.matrix(~1+x)
  Ul = list()
  u = unique(group)
  for (i in 1:m){
    Ul[[i]] = cbind(1,x[group==u[i]])
  } 
  U = bdiag(Ul)
  
  # Cov matrix
  Vfn = function(theta) {
    r2 = theta[3]
    tau01 = r2*sqrt(theta[1]*theta[2])
    # 2X2 matrix of tau parameters
    mm = matrix(c(theta[1], tau01, tau01, theta[2]), nrow = 2, byrow = T)
    mlist = list()
    for(i in 1:m){
      mlist[[i]] = mm
    }
    G = bdiag(mlist)
    
    R = theta[4]*diag(n)
    as.matrix(U %*% G %*% t(U) + R)
  }
  
  # estim beta using hat(cov)
  betahatfn = function(V) {
    W = solve(V)
    t_X.W.X = t(X) %*% W %*% X
    solve(t_X.W.X) %*% t(X) %*% W %*% y
  }
  # profile likelihood, ML estimator
  # if true REML
  lfn = function(theta) {
    V = Vfn(theta)
    W = solve(V)
    epsilonhat = y - X %*% betahatfn(V)
    l =
      -.5 * determinant(V)$modulus- .5 * t(epsilonhat) %*% W %*% epsilonhat
    if (REML)
      l = l - .5 * determinant(t(X) %*% W %*% X)$modulus
    l
  }
  opt = optim(start, lfn, method = "L-BFGS-B",control = list(fnscale = -1),
              lower = c(0,0,-1,0), upper = c(Inf,Inf,1,Inf))
  theta = opt$par
  betahat = betahatfn(Vfn(theta))
  W = solve(Vfn(theta))
  var_beta = solve(t(X) %*% W %*%X)
  sd_beta = sqrt(diag(var_beta))
  cor_beta = var_beta[1,2]/(sd_beta[1]*sd_beta[2])
  Fixed_ef = data.frame(Estimate = betahat, Std_Error = sd_beta)
  #list(theta = theta, beta = betahat, sd_beta = sd_beta, cor_beta = cor_beta)
  list(theta = theta, Fixed_ef =Fixed_ef,  cor_beta = cor_beta)

}

library(glmmTMB)
mod <- glmmTMB(goals ~ home + (1|attack) + (1|defence), poisson, data=long, REML=TRUE)

  • Given the random effects γai,γdjγai,γdj and the covariate xkxk the responses YijkYijk are conditionally independent and the conditional distribution f(yijk∣γai,γdj)f(yijk∣γai,γdj) is Poisson.

  • The conditional mean μijk=E(Yijk∣γai,γdj)μijk=E(Yijk∣γai,γdj) is linked to the linear predictor ηij=β0+β1xk+γai+γdjηij=β0+β1xk+γai+γdj through the link function

    ηijk=g(μijk),ηijk=g(μijk),
    or
    μij=h(ηij)μij=h(ηij)
     where h−1=gh−1=g. Here we use the log link function.

  • The random effects γai,γdjγai,γdj, i=1,…,m,i=1,…,m, j=1,…,mj=1,…,m, i≠ji≠j are independent and identically distributed

    γai∼N(0,τa) and γdj∼N(0,τd).γai∼N(0,τa) and γdj∼N(0,τd).
    These random effects represent the attack and defence strengths of each team. Note that γaiγai and γaiγai are assumed to be independent.

The model yijk=exp(β0+β1xk+γai+γdi)yijk=exp⁡(β0+β1xk+γai+γdi) gives the expected number of goals that the “attack” team ii will score if it plays against “defence” team j.j. The dummy variable xkxk represent the factor home having 2 levels (k=1,2k=1,2) and it is equal to 1 for k=2k=2 meaning that the “attack” team ii has home field advantage or 0 if k=1k=1 meaning that the “defence” team jj has home field advantage.

First, it holds that if a random variable Y=ln(X)Y=ln⁡(X) follows a normal distribution with mean 0 and variance τ2,τ2, then X follows a Lognormal distribution with mean exp(τ22)exp⁡(τ22) and variance (exp(τ2)−1)exp(τ2).(exp⁡(τ2)−1)exp⁡(τ2).

Since the random variables γa∼N(0,τ2a)γa∼N(0,τa2) and γd∼N(0,τ2d)γd∼N(0,τd2) are independent, the sum is normally distributed with mean equal to the sum of the corresponding means and variance equal to the sum of the corresponding variances. We write that

γa+γd∼N(0,τ2),γa+γd∼N(0,τ2),
where τ2=τ2a+τ2d.τ2=τa2+τd2.

The test of significance of random effects γa∼N(0.τ2a)γa∼N(0.τa2) and γd∼N(0.τ2d)γd∼N(0.τd2) is equivalent to testing if the variance of each random effect τ2aτa2 and τ2dτd2 is 0 or greater than 0. We construct the following hypothesis testing

Ho:τ2a=0 vs Ha:τ2a>0Ho:τa2=0 vs Ha:τa2>0
for testing if the random effect of attack is significant and the same holds for defence as well.

e)

rankings = function(data) {
  data = data[complete.cases(data),]
  tmp =
    data.frame(
      team = levels(data$attack),
      points = 0,
      goalsscored = 0,
      goalsconceeded = 0,
      scorediff = 0
    )
  # add points to each team going through each match separately
  for (i in seq(1, nrow(data), by = 2)) {
    j = data[i,]$attack
    k = data[i,]$defence
    if (data[i,]$goals > data[i + 1,]$goals)
      tmp[tmp$team == j,]$points =
      tmp[tmp$team == j,]$points + 3 # team j won
    else if (data[i,]$goals < data[i + 1,]$goals)
      tmp[tmp$team == k,]$points =
      tmp[tmp$team == k,]$points + 3 # team k won
    else {
      tmp[tmp$team == j,]$points =
        tmp[tmp$team == j,]$points + 1 # draw
      tmp[tmp$team == k,]$points =
        tmp[tmp$team == k,]$points + 1
    }
  }
  # compute goal differences and goals scored
  for (j in levels(data$attack)) {
    tmp[tmp$team == j, ]$goalsscored =
      sum(data[data$attack == j,]$goals)
    tmp[tmp$team == j, ]$goalsconceeded =
      sum(data[data$defence == j,]$goals)
  }
  tmp$scorediff = tmp$goalsscored - tmp$goalsconceeded
  # compute the rankings
  tmp$rank = data.table::frankv(
    tmp,
    col = c("points", "scorediff", "goalsscored"),
    ties.method = "random",
    order = -1
  )
  # return everything
  tmp[order(tmp$points, decreasing = T),]
}
rnk  = rankings(long)
rownames(rnk) = NULL

Simulating the remaining matches
lambdas = predict(mod, newdata = long[!complete.cases(long),], type = "response")
sim_rank = matrix(NA,nrow = 1000, ncol = 16)

for (i in 1:1000) {
  res = long
  res$goals[!complete.cases(res$goals)] = rpois(length(lambdas), lambda = lambdas)
  r = rankings(res)
  sim_rank[i,] = as.character(r$team)
}

nm = levels(long$attack) # team names
lnm = length(nm) # total number of teams
probs = matrix(0, nrow = lnm, ncol = lnm) # matrix to store the probabilities of rankings
rownames(probs) = nm
colnames(probs) = paste0(1:lnm,"-place")

for (j in 1:ncol(sim_rank)) {
  prob = table(sim_rank[,j])/1000 # calculate probabilities of j-th place
  nms = names(prob) # team names of corresponding probabilities
  for(i in 1:length(prob)){
    ind = which(nm == nms[i]) # find row of i-th name
    probs[ind,j] = as.numeric(prob[i]) # store probability
  }
}

library(ggplot2)
nm = levels(long$attack)
pos = matrix(NA, nrow = nrow(sim_rank), ncol = ncol(sim_rank))

  pos[i,] =  match(nm, sim_rank[i,])
}

pos = data.frame(pos)
colnames(pos)  = nm
pos_plot = tidyr::gather(pos, key = "team", value = "pos")
ggplot(data = pos_plot, aes(pos)) + geom_bar() + facet_wrap(~team)

We observe that the uncertainty regarding the first and last ranking positions is smaller compared to the in between rankings.

exp_pos  = colMeans(pos)
sd_pos = apply(pos,2,sd)/sqrt(1000)
dfplot = data.frame(team = nm, exp_pos = exp_pos, sd_pos = sd_pos, strength = m$strength)
bs = lm(exp_pos~strength, data = dfplot)$coefficients
pd <- position_dodge(0.1) 
ggplot(dfplot, aes(x=strength, y=exp_pos, colour = team)) + 
  geom_point()+
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=exp_pos-1.96*sd_pos, ymax=exp_pos+1.96*sd_pos)) +
  geom_abline(intercept = bs[1] ,slope = bs[2], colour = "grey")

Unsurprisingly, in the plot it seems that there is a strong relation between the expected ranking and team strengths. The relationship between the estimated expected rankings based on simulation of the whole series and the difference between attack and defence strength of each team does not seem to be completely montonic but this may be because of Monte carlo error so it remains somewhat unclear if the relationship is monotonic or not.
